should try `ManagedFd` + https://github.com/openbmc/stdplus/blob/ea1dc9348636e5d84331cc4e6a2eaa3d55680afc/include-fd/stdplus/fd/ops.hpp#L143-L147
Thanks!
should return the ec instead of throw.
Thanks!
Command success
Done
May be worth commenting that prior file contents are removed (e.g. previous second byte); we're not just overwriting individual bytes and keeping previous content.
Done

This took forever to figure out - but for whatever reason, the tmp file when written to initially by ManagedFd doesn't get read successfully in Jenkins CI run (passes on local CI). By doing a dummy write to create this file, it seems to be happy enough to pass the test. Tested that on a BMC, this works as intended.
I don't think you need the struct here either since you don't instantiate it. Just a length variable.
Done
Not used, I think it's probably trivial to understand the response format without it
Acknowledged
Technically this is safe because `sizeof(length) == 1`. But it would be preferrable to check if `data.size() < sizeof(length)` as that's the semantics if length were a different size.
I was doing data.empty() check before accessing data[0] to get the length - are you saying we don't need to worry about data being empty?
Oh whoa, that's an awesome function. Thanks!
I don't think you need to worry about it being too large, the function that writes it out later can just accept all the bytes.
Acknowledged
Should we just ignore extra padded data? Why even have a length prefix at all if you can tell the data length from the ipmi message?
Right yea, we will just do a `data.size() - 1 != payloadSize` check (I think that's what you mean?)

Just curious based on the code, I guess:
1. the payload size is always MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE?
2. data resides in the payload is always pushed to the end?

1. Yes, the MAX_PAYLOAD_SIZE is common across all the OEM handlers (I believe as part of the IPMI spec
2. Right, that's what we agreed upon in the README.md between the consumer / user of this IPMI command and it's common to have a size byte followed by the payload bytes.
It would be preferrable to have this be `payload.subspan(1, payloadSize)`, as last would behave differently if you allowed extra data.
Ah, ok - yeah Hao suggested this offline but I thought .last would be cleaner. Let me just do a subspan instead.
You shouldn't need to re-read the contents. We need to have some trust the system correctly writes files.
Acknowledged
is this cast needed?

Hmmm probably not but others had it in this repo so just copied it over.
